<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="2936" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[160,1155,1599,1728]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936">
No 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[231,323,1599,1624]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Chlorion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[231,323,1599,1624]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936">Chlorion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cocoon has been described in detail. 
<bibRefCitation author="Evans HE" box="[744,878,1599,1624]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936" pagination="235 - 299" refId="ref4688" refString="Evans HE. 1964. Further studies on the larvae of digger wasps (Hymenoptera: Sphecidae). Trans Am Entomol Soc. 90: 235 - 299 + pls VIII - XIX." type="journal article" year="1964">Evans (1964</bibRefCitation>
, p. 244) studied cocoons of 
<taxonomicName authority="Patton, 1879" authorityName="Patton" authorityYear="1879" box="[188,460,1634,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Chlorion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aerarium">
<emphasis box="[188,314,1634,1659]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936">C. aerarium</emphasis>
Patton, 1879
</taxonomicName>
and commented that they ‘were composed of a single layer of brittle, dark brown, transversely ribbed parchment-like material’ and that they were very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Klug" authorityYear="1801" box="[371,484,1703,1728]" class="Insecta" family="Sphecidae" genus="Sceliphron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[371,484,1703,1728]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2936">Sceliphron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
